Showa Shell Posts Impairment Loss as Solar Frontier Profit Shrinks





Showa Shell Posts Impairment Loss as Solar Frontier Profit Shrinks


2017/02/10 14:53

Kenji Kaneko, Nikkei BP CleanTech Institute


















Solar Frontier's new product for residential houses (source: Solar Frontier)



Showa Shell Sekiyu KK announced Feb 6, 2017, that it will register a fixed asset impairment loss (extraordinary loss) of ¥10.7 billion (approx US$94.4 million) for the consolidated results of the term ending in December 2016 in the wake of the business downturn of Solar Frontier KK (Minato-ku, Tokyo).

The profitability of Solar Frontier is drastically lowering due to the worsening of its business environment. According to Showa Shell Sekiyu, the fixed assets of the Kunitomi Plant in Miyazaki Prefecture, which is Solar Frontier's main factory, are showing a sign of an impairment loss. Therefore, Showa Shell Sekiyu decided to post an impairment loss of ¥10.7 billion for the fourth quarter of the fiscal year ending Dec 31, 2016, as an extraordinary loss.

Nevertheless, in the consolidated earnings of Showa Shell Sekiyu, the increase in the amount of the financial impact of inventory valuation caused by the higher-than-expected oil price, etc offset the extraordinary loss. As a result, Showa Shell Sekiyu's operating profit and ordinary profit are expected to be higher than the previous forecasts.

Solar Frontier's business environment is worsening mainly because the price of solar panels in overseas market is sharply dropping. China-based solar panel manufactures that have excessive production capacities are reportedly selling their products aggressively by cutting prices.

Solar Frontier recently built the Tohoku Plant, aiming to achieve "one of the world's highest cost competitivenesses" higher than that of the Kunitomi Plant. But it is not in full operation yet.

Therefore, Solar Frontier is making efforts to, for example, tap the market for residential panels in Japan, which is relatively profitable (See related article), by, for example, releasing a new product for residential use.






